Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Review report
Foreword
Taxes are the main source of income for public budgets.
A focus of the work of the auditors should therefore be on examining this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone causes an estimated €100 billion in tax losses in the European Union every year.
Already at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn in 2005, the participants pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.
This enables the auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimise audit practice.
VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, for the first time, the auditors of both countries examined the UST in parallel.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since UST fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the courts of auditors is needed, which will allow for a comprehensive assessment of whether the measures taken are suitable to deal effectively with UST fraud.
The two auditors decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of VAT in the Czech Republic and in the Federal Republic of Germany report on the audit.
1. Introduction
Exam number: (CZ) 09 / 11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of examination: (CZ) Administration of the UST (D) Bilateral Audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (NKÚ), Audit
Audit target:
(CZ) The UST administration and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic (CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (Germany) should be reviewed, and the procedures used by the financial authorities in the field of mutual assistance should also be investigated.
(D) The audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the auditors.
In addition, other test fields linked to the USt should be processed.
The findings made here should be compared to determine whether the tax procedures can be optimised.
The audit period was from 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period before the audit period until the conclusion of the audit.
2. Summary of the results and assessment of the parallel audit
The auditors of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to carry out an audit of the administration of the UST.
In the previous parallel investigation, they had uncovered suspicions of intra-Community transactions,
Which made a re-examination seem appropriate.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two auditors made recommendations on the management of the UST.
The aim of the review was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented and to examine the suspected cases identified.
The audit also looked at other issues, including selected cases of high-risk intra-Community transactions, mutual assistance in the recovery of UST claims and the UST audit of large companies.
The Court of Auditors found that:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit
• Recommendation 1: The rules governing the registration of taxable persons should be harmonised within the EU
During the first audit, the auditors compared the registration procedures for VAT in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxable persons within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to Council Regulation No 1798 / 2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the identification number of those subject to VAT.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxable persons and their possible deletion.
The auditors expected the Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the VAT system as early as possible, in line with their decision in principle.
On the final version of the draft, the Member States reached political agreement in Ecofin.
The aforementioned common rules are no longer included, and the two auditors regret that.
They still consider such regulations to be important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of the Summary Notices As a result of the first audit, the Court of Auditors recommended to the Member States that the Summary Notices (ZM) should be submitted on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community turnover could then be reviewed more quickly.
Council Directive 2008 / 117 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the common VAT system for the purpose of combating tax fraud in intra-Community transactions has reduced the deadline for the levy of the ZM to one month.
In the CZ, this requirement was implemented by an amendment to the USt Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
In Germany, the implementation did not enter into force until 1 July 2010, which meant that it did not transpose the obligation to levy the ZM on a monthly basis into national law on time.
• Recommendation 3: Data matching of the UST pre-registrations and the ZM in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to examine the merger of the procedures for UST pre-registrations and ZM The German financial administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Audit Office and has set up a working group to work out possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Audit Office will monitor the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level In the course of the first audit, the two auditors agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches to a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this does not happen, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The auditors found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems, which have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the information exchange system within the EU - Eurocanet, while the Federal Audit Office focused on German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
At the first audit, the auditors jointly examined transactions in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been carried out or which had been explained differently by the taxable persons of the two states in the UST preliminary filings (or UST declarations) or ZM.
The auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The audits by the tax offices of both states had not yet been completed at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.
The audit revealed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed, and the respective financial administrations have taken appropriate measures to do so (including subsequent VAT provisions or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Review of selected, particularly risky intra-Community sales
The audit also included highly risky intra-EU transactions between taxable persons in the EU covered by the Eurocanet system.
Eurocanet is used to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Member States can participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in Eurocanet. Germany has a passive status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of Eurocanet.
From the point of view of an active participant state, it is unsatisfactory that other Member States refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
The NKU identified both normal business incidents and those suspected of fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected sales.
This was particularly true for so-called "Missing Traders," where an audit of the documents alone is hardly enough to prove fraud to the taxpayer.
Suspected carousel fraud in imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities work more closely together in order to be able to track the proximity of goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final consumer.
Germany and a number of other countries have refused to take an active part in Eurocanet because they do not believe there is a sufficient legal basis.
The Federal Audit Office found that the German financial administration uses other tools to identify high-risk taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The Council of the EU agreed on a draft regulation,
Created by EUROFISC.
The experience gained so far with Eurocanet should feed into the planned network for the fight against VAT fraud.
4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
For this reason, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are handled in the same way.
The Federal Audit Office and the NKU compared the statistics that both Member States submitted to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two auditors consider a renewed discussion on statistics at EU level to be useful in order to avoid future disagreements.
If this does not happen, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should include more information on the VAT.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support Member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both auditors believe that Member States with a low recovery rate should strive to achieve at least the average recovery rate.
The Commission should support the Member States in this, if they so wish.
5. VAT audit at large companies
The auditors analysed the legal situation regarding the UST audit of large companies in both states.
In addition, they used a questionnaire to collect information from the financial authorities, which they considered important in this context.
It was clear that the situation in both countries is different.
For the selection of high-risk cases, the CZ has a system that includes a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT audits, balance sheet data, and profit and loss accounts).
As a result, the UST control can be effectively controlled and analysed.
In 2012, a special tax office for large companies will be set up.
There is no comparable system in Germany yet, which makes it difficult to control and analyse the overall UST control.
The German financial administration is focusing more on the selection of relevant individual cases and relies in particular on data from the UST pre-registration and / or UST declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are still to be improved, support the evaluation of this data.
