4. Audit of the management of VAT in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of Recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for the registration of taxable persons within the EU Protected
In response to the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors has recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adjusted and new rules for the deletion of registration in the CZ be introduced.
These amended rules should more effectively curb the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that the tax authorities did not delete the registration of taxable persons if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law No. 235 / 2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT Act").
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted an amendment to require the fä to be erased if taxpayers repeatedly fail to submit VAT declarations.
According to the Czech VAT law, the FA can delete the registration of a taxable person from office if (a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for 12 consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for this; (b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under the VAT law; (c) the taxable person no longer fulfils the requirements for the tax obligation.
The first audit showed that the Prague 1 FA, due to the existing legal situation, would have to cancel the registration of "foreign taxable persons" 3 with effect from 31 January of the following calendar year if they were not required to register and pay VAT in the current calendar year.
The Prague 1 FA often did not delete the VAT registration of these taxable persons because the relevant provision of the time limit could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the amendment to the US law, which came into force on 1 January 2009.
According to this, the FA has the power to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not provided taxable or tax-exempt goods or services in the previous calendar year and is entitled to a deduction.
Recommendation 2
Monthly levy of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the auditors recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council Directive, which shortened the turnaround for the levy of the ZM to one month, was implemented in the CZ by the UST Act, which came into force on 1 January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be issued if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with Section 9 (1) of the VAT Act are provided to a person registered in another Member State as subject to VAT.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services, as required by Council Directive 2008 / 8 / EC amending Directive 2006 / 112 / EC on the place of service.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the UST pre-registrations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data This recommendation referred to the German financial administration.
In its ATIS4 system, the Czech financial administration automatically compares data on intra-Community transactions from the UST declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the VAT is an essential prerequisite for the proper functioning of the EU's internal market.
That is why the fight against VAT fraud is of paramount interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is demonstrated, among other things, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In this report, an external expert estimated the loss of VAT for the 25 Member States in the period 2000 to 2006. After analysing the available data, the tax loss for the period mentioned was estimated at between 90 and 113 billion euros, based on the fact that the EU-25 lose an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated tax loss for the CZ in 2006 was 18%.
The first audit found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches to an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors has examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (Eurocanet).
For this purpose, taxable intra-EU transactions carried out and recorded in Eurocanet were selected (see Chapter 4.3).
The EUROFISC network aims to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat fraud more effectively, and to improve cooperation between the competent authorities in order to detect fraud as early as possible.
Later, EUROFISC could be used as a tool to assess the risk potential for intra-Community sales.
Ecofin Council 6 approved EUROFISC on 7 October 2008 and at the same time adopted the principles for the functioning of the system.
Eurocanet, which was developed by the Belgian financial administration in cooperation with the other Member States and with the support of the European Commission and OLAF7, serves as a model for EUROFISC.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky sales and to identify entrepreneurs involved in organised VAT fraud.
