4.2 Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
During the first audit, a joint investigation was carried out into transactions in which there were doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether there had been any discrepancies in the notifications of taxable persons in both Member States.
For the audit, the two auditors selected nine cases of intra-Community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany, where the tax audit by the threads of the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
1)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer purchased goods worth €22,686 from a German taxpayer.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his UST statement, because the period referred to in the German tax code did not have a UST identification number, but only a tax number for intra-German transactions.
Through international assistance in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that, according to German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods does not need a VAT identification number in order to be able to claim the tax exemption for intra-Community deliveries of goods.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that, according to an audit by the competent Czech FA, the Czech taxpayer submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the purchase of goods of the above value and at the same time claiming the same amount of deduction.
2)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer was reported to have purchased goods worth 12,561 euros from a German taxpayer.
However, he said he had not purchased the goods and therefore did not declare them in his UST statement.
The German financial administration, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, refused to process the request because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of €15,000.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain documents, the tax audit was inconclusive and the original tax fix remained in place.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA received two spontaneous information from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, according to which the German taxpayer had billed the delivery of the goods in question to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxpayer purchased the goods from the Slovak taxpayer and announced the acquisition in his regular VAT statement for the month of October 2004.
3)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxpayer was reported to have purchased a car worth 48 500 euros from a German taxpayer.
However, he did not declare an intra-Community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued a UST statement since August 2004, which is why the FA set the UST at 0 CZK for the quarter in question.
On the basis of information provided from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the FA asked the taxable person in March 2007 to submit a subsequent tax return, which the taxable person failed to do.
The audit found that the FA had carried out further audits in this tax case in 2007, finding that the car in question had been sold by the taxpayer to a used car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA imposed a predisposition for the tax period in December 2004, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The competent Czech court decided to open insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax debt is likely to be irrecoverable.
4)
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech taxpayer was reported to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) totalling 198 167 euros to Germany.
In response to a request for information under Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, it was stated that a tax penalty case was pending against the German taxpayer in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Federal Court of Auditors found that after the proceedings had been concluded, there was evidence that the German taxpayer was involved in fraud.
The intra-Community acquisition of goods was subject to labour market taxation in the amount of 182 424 euros (for 2004) and 369 690 euros (for 2005).
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech taxpayer was involved in carousel fraud involving new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German financial administration, a VAT audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the tax periods April, May and June 2005.
On the basis of the audit findings and information from the international exchange of information, the FA set an additional UST of 703 031 CZK for May 2005 and 726 551 CZK for June 2005.
5)
Czech taxpayer A is alleged to have purchased a machine with a total value of €58,000 from a German taxpayer in February 2005.
In the third quarter of 2004, the German taxpayer was reported to have delivered a machine worth 88 027 euros to Czech taxpayer B, but B denied the purchase.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that B had purchased the machine from a German company with a branch in the CZ.
Czech taxpayer A did not specify the purchase of the goods from the aforementioned German taxpayer in its VAT statement.
The German FA's response to a request for information under Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 showed that the German taxpayer had not made an intra-Community delivery of a machine worth 58 000 euros, but had made a delivery within the CZ.
In the inspection, the Federal Audit Office found that the intra-community delivery of the machine was classified as domestic delivery after the completion of an audit and the exemption from VAT was subsequently failed.
6)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer allegedly delivered goods worth €11,600 to a Czech taxpayer.
The goods were purchased and later sold in Germany, in 2005.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA had made its assessment on the basis of a supplementary UST statement, which incorrectly identified acquisitions from another Member State, including acquisitions in the above amount.
The Federal Audit Office found that after receiving a response to a request for information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the German FA corrected the German taxpayer's UST statement and set an additional UST of 1,600 euros.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding US investment there, an investigation is under way.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has not yet been corrected, as in Germany only the taxable person who handed over the ZM can correct it.
7)
The competent Czech FA received a request for information from the German financial administration in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the question of the purchase of a car worth 47 400 euros by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
After an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA determined the tax liability of the Czech taxpayer at 0 CZK and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the purchase of the car by the Czech taxpayer.
The audit by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the registration of the Czech VAT payer had been deleted because he had failed to comply with his tax obligations.
The Czech FA had sent the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has not yet corrected his information in the ZM, but has appealed against the tax ruling.
8)
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxpayer supplied a Czech taxpayer with goods totalling €33 205, which he did not declare to be an intra-Community purchase.
The audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors found that the Czech FA investigated the reasons for the discrepancies.
For the first quarter of 2005, the Czech taxpayer made repeated subsequent statements.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of acquisitions in the amount of CZK 134 273 in the period from the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005, which was due to the fact that sales for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the UST statements made.
9)
In the third quarter of 2004, a German taxpayer delivered goods worth 46 854 euros to a Czech taxpayer.
For the same period, the Czech taxpayer declared the intra-Community purchase of goods worth only €14,856.
As part of the interstate exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003, the Czech FA reviewed the actual value of the delivery.
With the German answer to this question, three invoices were sent, which showed a total value of the delivered goods of 31 998 euros, i.e. an amount corresponding to the difference between the purchase declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the results of the audit carried out by the Czech Court of Auditors, the Czech taxpayer, following repeated warnings from the FA in January 2007, submitted a subsequent VAT declaration for the tax period of July 2004.
With this declaration, the taxable person simultaneously asserted his right to a deduction, so his tax liability for the tax period in question remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures relating to the sales selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial administrations in the CZ and Germany had taken appropriate measures (including subsequent VAT provisions or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of risky intra-Community transactions
4.3.1 Statements in the Czech Republic
Eurocanet can be an important source of information to identify taxable persons at risk in the Member State of acquisition.
In the CZ, the early-warning information obtained from Eurocanet will be reviewed by the relevant FA with the purchasers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, CZ has included information on sales and taxable suppliers deemed to be at risk in the Eurocanet system.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit,
Those entered into the Eurocanet by the financial administrations of other Member States either as suppliers or purchasers.
