As the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data on Eurocanet, it was not possible to determine whether suppliers with German VAT identification numbers were classified as risky by the German financial administration.
The audit identified both normal business incidents and those suspected of carousel fraud or other fraud.
In the cases in question, they exchanged information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003,
For example:
• They found no suspicion of risky sales when examining the early warning information.
The taxable persons in question were constantly monitored because their data was stored in Eurocanet.
• They failed to prove breaches of the rules for calculating the tax base and the VAT on the basis of the accounting documents submitted, even though they found discrepancies in the transport and storage of the goods or revealed business relationships with mailbox companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual business incidents was complicated because certain taxable persons did not cooperate with and could not be contacted.
The relevant experts reviewed most of the risky taxable persons and transactions mentioned in Eurocanet's early warning notices.
However, their options for checking risky sales, especially so-called "missing traders," are limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly prove the fraudulent behaviour of the taxpayer.
Stricter requirements for the registration of taxable persons for the purposes of VAT and greater flexibility in the deletion of registrations would help to combat VAT fraud.
